# Extract Commit Metadata Using `jj log` Templates ## Context You are a member of a data team maintaining a linear audit history in a Jujutsu (jj) repository. Your team needs a machine-readable snapshot of the commit log that captures key metadata fields for compliance and audit purposes. You will use `jj log` with a custom template to extract specific commit fields and write the output to a designated log file. ## Starting Environment A jj repository has already been initialized at `/home/user/project`. The repository contains a linear chain of **five commits** (excluding the root), each with a meaningful description representing data pipeline steps. The commits are on a bookmark named `audit-log`. You can verify the repo state by running: ``` cd /home/user/project jj log ``` The five commits have the following descriptions (oldest to newest): 1. `ingest raw data` 2. `validate schema` 3. `transform records` 4. `aggregate metrics` 5. `export results` The author name for all commits is `Audit Bot` and the author email is `audit@example.com`. ## Your Task You must run a single `jj log` command that: 1. Targets all non-root, non-working-copy commits in the repository (use the revset `roots(mutable())::@ ~ @` to select committed revisions excluding the current empty working-copy commit). 2. Uses `--no-graph` to suppress the graph decoration. 3. Uses a `--template` (or `-T`) that formats each commit as a single line with the following fields separated by a pipe character (`|`): - The short commit ID: `commit_id.short(8)` - The author name: `author.name()` - The author email: `author.email()` - The commit description stripped of its trailing newline: `description.first_line()` 4. Each record must end with a newline (`\n`). 5. Redirects the output to `/home/user/project/commit_log.txt`. ### Exact Template String The template string you must use is: ``` commit_id.short(8) ++ "|" ++ author.name() ++ "|" ++ author.email() ++ "|" ++ description.first_line() ++ "\n" ``` ### Exact Command to Run ```bash cd /home/user/project && jj log --no-graph -r 'roots(mutable())::@ ~ @' -T 'commit_id.short(8) ++ "|" ++ author.name() ++ "|" ++ author.email() ++ "|" ++ description.first_line() ++ "\n"' > /home/user/project/commit_log.txt ``` ## Expected Output The file `/home/user/project/commit_log.txt` must contain exactly **5 lines** (one per committed revision), ordered from **oldest to newest** (i.e., use `--reversed` flag in addition). Each line follows the format: ``` <8-char-commit-id>|Audit Bot|audit@example.com|<description> ``` ### Revised Exact Command (with `--reversed` for oldest-first ordering) ```bash cd /home/user/project && jj log --no-graph --reversed -r 'roots(mutable())::@ ~ @' -T 'commit_id.short(8) ++ "|" ++ author.name() ++ "|" ++ author.email() ++ "|" ++ description.first_line() ++ "\n"' > /home/user/project/commit_log.txt ``` Example output (commit IDs will differ): ``` a1b2c3d4|Audit Bot|audit@example.com|ingest raw data e5f6a7b8|Audit Bot|audit@example.com|validate schema c9d0e1f2|Audit Bot|audit@example.com|transform records 34567890|Audit Bot|audit@example.com|aggregate metrics abcdef12|Audit Bot|audit@example.com|export results ``` ## Verification Conditions The automated verifier will: 1. Check that the file `/home/user/project/commit_log.txt` exists. 2. Check that the file contains exactly 5 non-empty lines. 3. Check that each line matches the pattern `^[0-9a-f]{8}\|Audit Bot\|audit@example.com\|.+$`. 4. Check that line 1 ends with `|ingest raw data`. 5. Check that line 2 ends with `|validate schema`. 6. Check that line 3 ends with `|transform records`. 7. Check that line 4 ends with `|aggregate metrics`. 8. Check that line 5 ends with `|export results`. 9. Check that the commit IDs in the file correspond to real commits in the jj repository. ## Notes - Do **not** use `git` commands; use only `jj` commands. - The `jj` binary is available in your PATH. - No `sudo` or root access is required. - The output file must be at the exact path `/home/user/project/commit_log.txt`. - Make sure you run the command from within the `/home/user/project` directory or pass `-R /home/user/project` to jj.   

